  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Response to the Food Crisis in Vulnerable Communities in Guatemala</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">1) Raise awareness and increase organisational capacity in communities and at the municipal level; 2) Training and technical assistance at the community level; 3) Establishment of productive systems; 4) Training in improved nutrition and food choices; and 5) Development of commercial strategies.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Indigenous population, Rural populations</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Low productivity, increase in production costs, limited access to land and water for agricultural use, increase in unemployment rates, lack of agricultural extension services, post-harvest losses and climate threats are the major factors which influence the capacity of families to adequately access food and nourishment in poor, rural indigenous communities in Northern Guatemala. This situation has become more acute with the current rise in prices of basic food staples, which is intimately linked to poverty which affects over 6.6 million Guatemalans. This project is an immediate response to the scarcity of food due to the raise in food prices. It is increasing and diversifying agricultural productivity to increase family income. It also aims to improve the capacity of communities to respond in the future to food shocks. The main components of the project are to: (1) raise awareness and increase organizational capacity in communities and at the municipal level; (2) training and technical assistance at community level; (3) establishment of productive systems; (4) training in improved nutrition and food choices; and (5) development of commercial strategies.</narrative>
  </description>
